most of my time just parenting.

00:03:07.479 --> 00:03:11.839
Well, thank you so much for joining us as we kind of wait for questions to come

00:03:11.839 --> 00:03:13.639
in from everybody in the audience here.

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:17.919
I'm curious if you could kind of give us a little insight into some of the

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:22.119
problems that your team is trying to help solve or things that you're working on.

00:03:22.479 --> 00:03:25.000
So you can put us in your, your frame of reference.

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:26.119
Cool.

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:26.360
Yeah.

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:27.960
I'll let me talk about a couple of things.

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:33.240
So, um, at Stripe, we're interested in forecasting as many businesses are in

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:36.559
understanding how much payment volume are we going to have next year?

00:03:36.559 --> 00:03:38.479
How many active users will we have?

00:03:38.759 --> 00:03:39.960
What will our uptime be?

00:03:40.279 --> 00:03:45.000
There's a number of forecasting problems that come, uh, they come into play that,

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:46.360
you know, are a business advantage.

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:50.080
If we are good at them, we can set the budget, we can set our targets, we

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:52.320
can direct our efforts appropriately.

00:03:52.679 --> 00:03:56.320
Um, and so my team is, spends a lot of time thinking about how we can

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:58.119
produce the best forecast for Stripe.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:01.800
Um, I really, as a side note, I like forecasting as a data science area,

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.399
because it's not one that you always learn about in a machine learning course

00:04:05.399 --> 00:04:10.800
or spend a lot of time thinking about in, um, your, you know, more formal education.

00:04:10.839 --> 00:04:11.559
I didn't at least.

00:04:12.039 --> 00:04:16.359
Um, but now in, you know, sort of on the business side, it's an extremely

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:20.399
practical, uh, business problem to be able to solve at the same time.

00:04:20.399 --> 00:04:21.880
It's very interesting statistically.

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:26.160
And there's a lot of work that we do, um, to, you know, sort of experiment and find

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:28.079
the best methods for doing forecasting.

00:04:28.679 --> 00:04:32.559
Um, so we do what's called hierarchical forecasting.

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:36.239
So this means that we want to have a forecast for Stripe overall.

00:04:36.279 --> 00:04:38.200
We want to know, you know, what's our total payment volume going

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:39.200
to be for the whole company.

00:04:39.559 --> 00:04:41.920
But we also want to know what is it going to be for each region?

00:04:41.959 --> 00:04:43.559
What is it going to be for each business type?

00:04:43.559 --> 00:04:44.799
What's it going to be for each cohort?

00:04:44.799 --> 00:04:46.720
There's all these dimensions that flow down.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:49.000
So you can kind of think of this as a hierarchy, right?

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.359
Where all of the dimensions, um, then need to add up to the total, right?

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:55.000
We have to have a coherent hierarchy.

00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:56.079
That's how we talk about it.

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:00.880
Uh, and so we use, uh, this method where we can actually choose

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:02.359
any forecasting method we want.

00:05:02.799 --> 00:05:06.440
Um, for each node of the hierarchy, you know, we use a lot of classical

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:10.000
forecasting methods like ARIMA and exponential smoothing, um, we also

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.559
experiment with other types of methods.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:16.079
Um, and we use those to make estimates and then we apply sort of a meta model

00:05:16.119 --> 00:05:21.040
on top of it, hierarchical reconciliation, um, to basically tweak each forecast

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:25.320
as little as possible so that they all still add up to the total forecast.

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:29.279
And that then, you know, we apply, um, some additional adjustments on top

00:05:29.279 --> 00:05:31.760
of that, and that becomes the budget for the company.

00:05:33.559 --> 00:05:34.040
Thank you.

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:36.799
I, I see Mark had a follow-up question on that.

00:05:36.799 --> 00:05:38.679
Mark, do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:40.519
Yeah, sure.

