00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:14.320
Um, you know, everyone, a lot of data scientists have interesting

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:15.679
or unusual career paths.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.919
I'm no exception here.

00:09:17.919 --> 00:09:22.000
So I was, I did my PhD in computational immunology.

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:26.039
Um, it actually started out as a PhD in pure immunology.

00:09:26.039 --> 00:09:30.440
So I was a wet lab biologist, you know, pipetting and doing experiments.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:37.159
Um, I realized pretty quickly in my PhD, um, I took an R class and a Python class.

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:41.320
And, um, then I took, you know, more CS courses and I did more

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:42.880
statistics and machine learning.

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:46.640
Um, you know, realized pretty quickly that that was a direction that would

00:09:46.679 --> 00:09:48.280
enable me to be a better biologist.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.799
And also just an area of a lot of interest for me.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:54.599
Um, you know, I was lucky enough to be able to do a ton of coursework and

00:09:54.599 --> 00:09:57.080
really direct my research that direction.

00:09:57.080 --> 00:10:00.520
So by the time I finished my PhD, I was doing fully computational work.

00:10:01.039 --> 00:10:04.440
Um, when I finished up, I thought, what do I want to do next?

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:09.239
Um, I, uh, really enjoyed academia, had a great time there, thought very

00:10:09.239 --> 00:10:10.960
seriously about academic postdocs.

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:14.320
Um, and then also thought, you know, I really liked this data

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:15.479
side of what I've been doing.

00:10:15.479 --> 00:10:18.919
I really liked the statistics and the ML and all the programming that I've been doing.

00:10:19.359 --> 00:10:21.239
Um, and so I looked at data science positions as well.

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:22.239
So I applied to both.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:27.919
Um, and in the end I, uh, decided to take a data science position because I felt

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:31.520
like it was much more different than what I had done before and that I would learn

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:36.479
more in that position just because, um, it would really force me to, uh, continue

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:41.320
to build the skills that I had started to develop in my PhD and put me into an,

00:10:41.679 --> 00:10:44.479
you know, entirely new problem space that I hadn't been before.

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:46.239
Um, so that's what I did.

00:10:46.239 --> 00:10:50.640
I went first to a small health insurance startup called collective health.

00:10:50.840 --> 00:10:52.719
I was there for two years.

00:10:53.119 --> 00:10:57.359
Um, a great thing about going to a startup is you learn a lot of data engineering.

00:10:57.479 --> 00:11:01.479
And so I, you know, spent a lot of time building pipelines and really getting

00:11:01.479 --> 00:11:06.520
to know, uh, you know, sort of bolstering how you actually write code in a, uh,

00:11:06.559 --> 00:11:08.719
environment with other people, right.

00:11:08.719 --> 00:11:11.640
When your PhD, it's very much just sort of you and your notebook.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:16.440
And this was now actually having to, uh, write in a more production environment.

00:11:16.919 --> 00:11:21.479
Um, so learned a lot there and I did health insurance thinking that it would be

00:11:21.479 --> 00:11:26.159
somewhat related to my PhD work, which was on HIV and the immune system.

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:31.080
Um, it turns out not really that much, that much, uh, overlap between those two

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:31.840
subject areas.

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:36.119
Um, but I really loved the data science side of things and I really loved having

00:11:36.119 --> 00:11:40.719
impact in business and being able to see the results of my work more directly.

00:11:41.239 --> 00:11:44.919
Um, so after a couple of years, I decided to move over to Stripe.

00:11:45.359 --> 00:11:53.039
Um, Stripe was very appealing because it was, um, it was still, it was big enough

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:55.520
to have invested in data infrastructure.

00:11:55.559 --> 00:11:57.119
There was a ton of data available.

00:11:57.479 --> 00:12:02.559
Um, you know, I was going to be able to do more statistical and ML type work, but it

00:12:02.559 --> 00:12:06.239
was still small enough that there were a lot of unsolved problems, which is actually,

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:08.280
you know, five years later, still true with Stripe today.

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:14.400
Um, and so that's what made me decide to, that I, you know, was more interested in

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:18.159
the data problems rather than focused on a particular domain.

00:12:18.799 --> 00:12:23.479
Um, it has turned out that financial payments, um, are a complex system, just

00:12:23.479 --> 00:12:25.200
like the immune system is a complex system.

00:12:25.239 --> 00:12:29.520
So even though I do not use my domain knowledge for my PhD that much, I still

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:30.880
use a lot of the skills that I learned.

00:12:30.880 --> 00:12:36.239
I still use, you know, a lot of the, um, how to present, how to do research, how

00:12:36.239 --> 00:12:40.559
to think about problems, how to break down complex problems, um, all the time.

00:12:40.599 --> 00:12:44.799
And so, you know, really have found that, um, if you think about it the right way,

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:46.159
you know, skills are pretty transferable.

00:12:48.719 --> 00:12:49.520
Absolutely.

