it the statistical forecasting and the adjustments, you know, it was all done

00:14:10.039 --> 00:14:11.960
in spreadsheets by finance folks.

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:15.719
And we did really have to prove our value of, you know, how does, um, a

00:14:15.719 --> 00:14:17.640
statistical model actually help.

00:14:18.159 --> 00:14:21.880
Um, so our current system is we have, you know, the statistical model.

00:14:21.919 --> 00:14:25.599
We actually do, um, you know, that's all done by data science.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.039
Um, we do backtesting and reports to be able to, you know, build confidence

00:14:30.039 --> 00:14:33.440
in each level of the hierarchy so that people can understand where do they

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:37.159
expect accuracy, where do they expect less accuracy, um, and then we have a

00:14:37.159 --> 00:14:41.760
whole process with the finance and strategy team where they, um, make

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:45.719
adjustment to the forecast and, you know, are pretty clear about where they

00:14:45.719 --> 00:14:49.000
are doing adjustments and how, uh, how it's affecting the total.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:52.679
And then we track both the statistical versus the adjusted forecast.

00:14:52.679 --> 00:14:56.280
And what we've learned over time is that making adjustments in certain ways

00:14:56.280 --> 00:14:59.119
or certain places is very important and very effective.

00:14:59.599 --> 00:15:03.479
Um, and we sort of encouraged the finance and strategy team to focus their

00:15:03.479 --> 00:15:06.919
efforts there, whereas, you know, in other places, the statistical model is

00:15:06.919 --> 00:15:10.960
quite accurate and it's best to spend effort elsewhere.

00:15:11.159 --> 00:15:15.679
Um, so that's, uh, that's the baseline of how we think about it.

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:20.239
Um, you know, again, ever evolving, um, but also we also have an embedded model,

00:15:20.239 --> 00:15:20.400
right?

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:21.880
So we sit with finance and strategy.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:23.200
We work really closely with them.

00:15:23.559 --> 00:15:25.400
Um, we really understand their problems.

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:29.719
It's very much a like partnership type model rather than a, you know, throw

00:15:29.719 --> 00:15:31.119
a model over the wall type model.

00:15:34.479 --> 00:15:34.919
Yeah, it does.

00:15:34.919 --> 00:15:38.719
It's really, um, and it sounds like for having been sort of driving it for

00:15:39.239 --> 00:15:43.280
relatively small handful of years, it sounds really mature and really, um, like,

00:15:43.479 --> 00:15:47.760
uh, uh, comprehensive in a, in a bunch of ways that I think are really impressive.

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:48.960
So yeah, it's cool.

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:50.039
Thank you.

00:15:50.039 --> 00:15:54.400
It's, uh, we still have a lot more that we would like to do for sure.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:54.719
Yeah.

00:15:55.599 --> 00:15:58.280
There's a whole literature about adjustments and the best way to do that.

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:01.280
And we applied some of those things, but there's so much more that I think we

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:03.239
could do to really maximize our effort.

00:16:03.799 --> 00:16:04.000
Yeah.

00:16:04.679 --> 00:16:05.080
Thank you.

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:09.200
I know you just said you sit with the finance and strategy team.

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:14.239
So I was curious, is there like a general data science team for the

00:16:14.239 --> 00:16:18.159
whole company or is there data science team, like pockets within each group?

00:16:18.719 --> 00:16:18.960
Yep.

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:21.799
So general data science team, and I'm using sit with, to be clear, I'm

00:16:21.799 --> 00:16:23.559
using sit with someone here.

00:16:23.719 --> 00:16:27.359
We used to sit with them when we were fully in office and now it's, um, you

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:30.559
know, sit with them on zoom, but, um, centralized data science team.

00:16:30.599 --> 00:16:32.479
So we have a hybrid embedded model.

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:36.359
Um, data scientists has a partner team that they work really closely with, right?

00:16:36.359 --> 00:16:39.320
So I'm on the business side with the finance and operations teams.

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:41.919
Others might work with product or engineering teams.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.119
Um, and we really, you know, act like members of that team, get to know their

00:16:45.119 --> 00:16:48.200
problems, get to under, you know, attend their meetings, their offsides,

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:51.599
understand what's going on with them and do joint planning together.

00:16:51.679 --> 00:16:55.000
And so we like to think it's, you know, best of both worlds, making sure we

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.760
are solving real business problems.

00:16:56.760 --> 00:16:59.840
But the centralized data science team keeps us pushing the envelope

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:01.679
technologically and innovatively as well.

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:03.880
Yeah, that's really cool.

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:05.719
Uh, deep shy.

00:17:05.719 --> 00:17:08.000
So you had a question over on Slido.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:08.920
Do you want to ask that here?

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:10.680
Sure.

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:14.040
I, um, the druid cause Alan's question was slightly similar, but I'll

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:16.160
ask, um, slightly different way.

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:21.800
So you do get like finance and stakeholder buy-in, but sometimes if you, when you

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:27.199
just recently have started statistical finance models, what happens when you

00:17:27.239 --> 00:17:31.599
statistical finance models, what happens if it deflates what the

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:34.000
previous finance predictions were?

00:17:34.359 --> 00:17:35.880
And have you had such a scenario?

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:39.560
Cause those buy-ins are like so difficult and I've had set scenarios as well.

00:17:39.839 --> 00:17:41.359
So how do you get a buy-in there?

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:42.280
Yeah.

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:44.520
Um, it's a great question.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.560
As much as you can bring in confidence intervals or backtesting, you know,

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:50.680
statistics and show here's what we expect.

00:17:51.119 --> 00:17:54.839
Um, you know, those of course are only as good as your input data.

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:56.880
And that can be challenging when you're first starting out, but

00:17:57.199 --> 00:17:58.760
that is, you know, finance.

00:17:58.760 --> 00:18:00.040
Folks are very quantitative, right?

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:01.119
They're very data oriented.

00:18:01.119 --> 00:18:04.040
They want to know how, at least, you know, our, our finance folks are.

00:18:04.479 --> 00:18:08.640
Um, so that helps, uh, there's, you know, in our experience, it did

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:10.199
take some time just to build trust.

00:18:10.199 --> 00:18:14.719
And so it was making sure that we had all the very detailed tracking in place.

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:18.079
And so it wasn't saying, Hey, we're going to replace your model.

00:18:18.119 --> 00:18:19.400
It was saying, let's run them in parallel.

00:18:19.719 --> 00:18:19.959
Right.

00:18:19.959 --> 00:18:23.599
And let's just sort of track, you know, the statistical model, the finance

00:18:23.599 --> 00:18:25.280
model, maybe some combination of them.

00:18:25.319 --> 00:18:26.800
We want to do an adjusted model.

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:32.520
Um, and let's, you know, look for six months at how those go and see, um, you

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:36.199
know, let's just sort of be objective about it if we can, and that, um, that

00:18:36.199 --> 00:18:39.800
ultimately was, you know, very helpful for us in building some trust and

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:42.520
confidence, but it is, it is, you know, a relationship that just, it

00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:43.760
does take some time to build.

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:45.040
Definitely.

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:45.680
Thanks Tara.

00:18:48.119 --> 00:18:50.079
Thank you all for all the great questions too.

00:18:50.079 --> 00:18:54.800
I see, um, one on Slido was with your forecasting, how do you

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:57.160
share results to those who make decisions?

00:18:57.560 --> 00:18:59.520
Is it through Excel, PowerPoint?

00:18:59.839 --> 00:19:02.479
Do you ever use shiny or SharePoint, Power BI?

00:19:03.479 --> 00:19:04.199
Ah, I would love it.

00:19:04.199 --> 00:19:05.800
If we had shiny, we don't have it set up.

00:19:05.839 --> 00:19:06.640
Suddenly it's striped.

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:10.959
So we have our own internal rolled, um, forecasting site, not

00:19:10.959 --> 00:19:12.319
forecasting dashboarding tool.

00:19:12.319 --> 00:19:18.079
That is a SQL based and allows us to, um, sort of build, uh, pretty nice

00:19:18.079 --> 00:19:20.439
dashboards that way on our data.

00:19:20.439 --> 00:19:21.760
So we use a lot of that.

00:19:22.160 --> 00:19:27.160
Um, we will, you know, some, we, uh, we'll sometimes, you know, make sort of bespoke

00:19:27.199 --> 00:19:30.520
plots in R or Python and, um, share those.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:35.000
We do a lot of PowerPoint or, you know, Google slides presentations as well.

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:40.000
Um, and sometimes we, you know, when we're working directly with FNS, there

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:45.160
certainly are sort of queries and spreadsheets and, you know, that we try

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:46.560
to speak their language where we can.

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:49.880
So while we might operate in more of a SQL land, they might be operating

00:19:50.239 --> 00:19:51.199
of a spreadsheet land.

00:19:51.199 --> 00:19:53.160
And so we try to interface between those things.

00:19:55.520 --> 00:19:55.839
Great.

00:19:55.880 --> 00:19:56.439
Thank you.

00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:01.119
Um, Abigail, I love your question into the, in the chat.

00:20:01.119 --> 00:20:04.359
I know we get to hear a lot of different perspectives on this, this one

00:20:04.359 --> 00:20:06.079
and love to have you ask that here.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:13.239
Oh, I don't know if we can hear you yet, so I can ask it and feel

00:20:13.239 --> 00:20:15.319
free to jump in after if you want.

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:18.680
But the question was, how do you feel about being a manager versus

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:22.359
being in a purely SME individual contributor role?

00:20:22.400 --> 00:20:23.599
Do you still get to code?

00:20:24.719 --> 00:20:30.239
Um, these days, not as much when I, so I started as an IC at Stripe and, um, I

00:20:30.239 --> 00:20:32.079
transitioned about a year into my tenure.

00:20:32.079 --> 00:20:34.400
And when I first transitioned, you know, managing a small team,

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:36.079
I still did about 50% coding.

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:40.079
Um, and now I, you know, manage usually between eight to 10 folks.

00:20:40.079 --> 00:20:42.680
So I do, you know, more pure management stuff.

00:20:43.160 --> 00:20:45.719
Um, I think, you know, I've really enjoyed the transition.

00:20:45.719 --> 00:20:49.479
I've find that I think, you know, the key question to ask yourself, if

00:20:49.479 --> 00:20:53.239
you're thinking about IC versus management is, um, how motivated you

00:20:53.239 --> 00:20:58.880
will be by enabling other folks to do work versus, um, how, how motivated

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:02.880
are you by, you know, solving problems and shipping work, uh, yourself.

00:21:03.359 --> 00:21:06.359
And most people would be, you know, motivated by both of those things,

00:21:06.359 --> 00:21:09.520
but it's really sort of trying to figure out for yourself, um, where

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:13.959
you want to prioritize spending your time and how helpful, um, you know,

00:21:13.959 --> 00:21:16.839
each of those roles might be to you in achieving that goal.

00:21:17.839 --> 00:21:18.640
That's my short answer.

00:21:18.719 --> 00:21:20.319
I'm happy, happy to go on more.

00:21:20.319 --> 00:21:21.199
These are great questions.

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:23.199
Thank you.

00:21:24.839 --> 00:21:27.719
Um, Eugene, I see you had a question in the chat.

00:21:27.719 --> 00:21:28.839
Do you want to jump in next?

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:33.520
Sure.

00:21:33.520 --> 00:21:38.760
It's a, um, my question is just about the sophistication of modeling.

00:21:39.119 --> 00:21:44.119
So you, you seem to discuss quite a few rather sophisticated

00:21:44.119 --> 00:21:47.359
models in your forecasting, uh, as you gave the, your short sort

00:21:47.359 --> 00:21:49.319
of summary of, of what you're using.

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:55.000
And I'm just curious, has the increase in, I assume you started simple, right?

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:01.119
So has the increase in sophistication actually significantly changed, uh,

00:22:01.319 --> 00:22:06.119
your results or your outcomes, uh, as you've, you know, as the models have

00:22:06.119 --> 00:22:12.040
evolved, yeah, this is, um, it's a good question.

00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:17.160
So our forecast, I think the way that we do the hierarchical

00:22:17.199 --> 00:22:19.239
reconciliation is very important.

00:22:19.319 --> 00:22:23.000
And, um, you know, that has certainly increased in sophistication over time,

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:25.119
underlying models themselves.

00:22:25.119 --> 00:22:27.599
We actually don't use anything most of the time.

00:22:27.719 --> 00:22:30.479
Um, they're not super fancy forecasting models.

00:22:30.479 --> 00:22:33.800
We're not doing, um, you know, some of the things that are winning the

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:36.239
M5 forecasting competition these days.

00:22:36.239 --> 00:22:39.839
It's, you know, sort of bread and butter, um, ARIMA and exponential

00:22:39.839 --> 00:22:42.839
smoothing, um, for the most part, we, you know, we'll, we'll

00:22:42.839 --> 00:22:43.839
play with other models too.

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:48.079
Um, and we have found that for our particular business problem, that

00:22:48.079 --> 00:22:51.479
works really well because we have a decent amount of history.

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:54.280
We have, you know, very important to capture seasonality.

00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:55.719
We're doing monthly forecasts.

00:22:55.719 --> 00:22:59.599
So, uh, if we are able to capture what we need to capture for those models.

00:22:59.880 --> 00:23:04.040
So the choice of, uh, the choice of forecasting model is so dependent

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:10.520
on the problem that you have and the, um, you know, there, there's so many

00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:12.079
things to consider about your input data.

00:23:12.439 --> 00:23:17.079
I think if we had, um, you know, a lot of external regressors that we were

00:23:17.079 --> 00:23:21.839
trying to model a lot of sort of parallel processes happening, um, you

00:23:21.839 --> 00:23:24.680
know, then probably different kinds of models, potentially more of the deep

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:28.760
learning forecasting models that have come into play recently, uh, might be

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:30.119
really helpful to us as well.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:33.319
But, you know, for the most part, um, you know, a lot of, a lot of bread and

00:23:33.319 --> 00:23:34.800
butter forecasting models work well for us.

00:23:38.439 --> 00:23:38.839
Thank you.

00:23:38.839 --> 00:23:42.640
And Trevor, I know you had a somewhat similar question, so I just wanted to

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:45.959
see if that addressed your question too, or if you want to add on to that.

00:23:46.319 --> 00:23:47.000
Yeah.

00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:47.880
Hi, Rachel.

00:23:50.319 --> 00:23:56.400
It is indeed a connected question, you know, because the, so most

00:23:56.400 --> 00:24:01.719
forecasting models look at historical data to predict the future, right?

00:24:02.160 --> 00:24:05.760
So that is assuming that the past is the future, right?

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:08.640
And of course we understand that can change, right?

00:24:08.640 --> 00:24:12.479
So for example, when COVID came along, it disrupted many models, right?

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:16.880
Nobody could have forecasted that COVID would have had the effect

00:24:16.880 --> 00:24:19.119
that it had on businesses, right?

00:24:19.400 --> 00:24:28.239
So I'm just wondering, um, to what extent, Dara, there are factors that would not

00:24:28.239 --> 00:24:32.599
have been, been in your models that would have affected maybe the accuracy of your

00:24:32.599 --> 00:24:34.319
models, that's one.

00:24:34.319 --> 00:24:40.319
And two, we use historical data to make predictions at the end of the day.

00:24:41.839 --> 00:24:44.439
Let's say, let's say you're forecasting sales, right?

00:24:44.479 --> 00:24:47.920
And you'd have forecasted it to be a certain amount, right?

00:24:48.319 --> 00:24:49.719
Based on historical data.

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:54.400
But then when reality happens at the end of a period, you get the actual numbers.

00:24:54.680 --> 00:24:56.479
So I want to know two things, really.

00:24:57.560 --> 00:25:04.680
How close are you typically to your forecast and how do you manage factors

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:09.560
that weren't considered in the model in the first place because of, you know,

00:25:09.560 --> 00:25:10.760
you weren't thinking about those.

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:12.160
Um, I hope I'm clear.

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:13.800
Yeah.

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:17.520
Sort of some fundamental problems of forecasting in a business setting.

00:25:18.920 --> 00:25:21.359
We do include external regressors.

00:25:21.359 --> 00:25:26.520
And, um, now of course, like we didn't, we didn't predict COVID when I look back

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:30.959
now, like forecasting was so easy pre COVID and now post COVID it's, you know,

00:25:30.959 --> 00:25:32.000
a whole different ball game.

00:25:32.040 --> 00:25:35.959
Um, so now, you know, we do include regressors that try to sort of, um,

00:25:36.119 --> 00:25:39.680
account for the past COVID changes in our data.

00:25:39.760 --> 00:25:42.280
Um, what we don't want is to, you know, continue forecasting

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:43.599
more COVID in the future.

00:25:44.199 --> 00:25:49.439
So we do have some sort of external things that we use that help us to predict that.

00:25:49.439 --> 00:25:55.160
We also do factor in macroeconomic variables on top of our statistical forecast

00:25:55.160 --> 00:25:59.520
that, you know, Again, you still have to make your own predictions and sort of

00:25:59.520 --> 00:26:01.839
decide as a company, what you think might happen.

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:05.719
Uh, we do sometimes do scenario based planning as well, you know, baseline

00:26:05.719 --> 00:26:08.800
and here's sort of the upside or the downside scenario to try to give the

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:11.920
business some framework for how to think about possibilities.

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:16.400
Um, Accuracy and, you know, how, what do we do when the forecast is off?

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:20.040
So with the hierarchical forecast, you know, the general pattern is that we are

00:26:20.040 --> 00:26:24.319
not that accurate at the lowest levels of the hierarchy generally, you know, for

00:26:24.319 --> 00:26:30.520
forecasting, um, one cohort, one region, one business type that gets to be a

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:32.000
pretty small set of data.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.640
We don't have as much history, um, or there may be erratic patterns in it.

00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:38.839
And so we don't have as much accuracy, uh, down there, but then when you add

00:26:38.839 --> 00:26:43.760
up, um, to the total, you know, you have a much more robust data set and we tend

00:26:43.760 --> 00:26:47.160
to be more accurate at the higher levels of the forecast.

00:26:47.719 --> 00:26:50.439
Um, we do a lot of tracking, we create a lot of dashboards.

00:26:50.479 --> 00:26:54.079
We try to be really clear with, you know, where we're doing well and where we're

00:26:54.079 --> 00:27:00.800
not, um, we do re-forecast throughout the year to, um, be able to sort of update

00:27:01.239 --> 00:27:05.079
our best guess on where we think we're going to land given more data has

00:27:05.079 --> 00:27:06.280
come in throughout the year.

00:27:06.760 --> 00:27:08.920
Um, so that is helpful.

00:27:09.239 --> 00:27:12.719
And then we just sit side by side with finance and strategy and do the analysis

00:27:12.719 --> 00:27:15.800
and try to understand, you know, when the forecast was off, what are the

00:27:15.800 --> 00:27:17.160
segments in which it was off?

00:27:17.239 --> 00:27:18.920
Can we identify the root cause for that?

00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:22.520
And how can we improve our forecast model for the next iteration?

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:27.880
So no, no magic bullet certainly, but you know, a lot of continual efforts

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:29.479
to, you know, try to improve over time.

00:27:30.839 --> 00:27:31.400
Thank you.

00:27:32.800 --> 00:27:33.680
Thank you very much.

00:27:34.680 --> 00:27:36.599
And I meant to say this earlier too.

00:27:36.599 --> 00:27:41.119
I know that I get to know everybody when I see people every week, but when you ask

00:27:41.119 --> 00:27:43.680
your question, feel free to introduce yourself again.

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:50.199
