00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:38.320
Sure.

00:41:38.399 --> 00:41:40.919
Uh, I've got, I'm thinking of lots of, lots of questions today.

00:41:41.199 --> 00:41:46.399
Um, I I'm curious to how, if you have a balance that you can maintain between

00:41:46.479 --> 00:41:50.840
the sort of routine things like financial forecasting that has an annual cadence

00:41:50.840 --> 00:41:56.000
or a quarterly requirement or whatever, with room to like experiment and learn

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:01.719
new methods, um, try out tools, shop those around into the organization.

00:42:02.040 --> 00:42:06.199
And how do you, how do you meet all those needed commitments with, how do you

00:42:06.199 --> 00:42:11.679
balance that with like room to explore room to grow for your team to make sure

00:42:11.679 --> 00:42:16.600
that they're, um, you know, uh, able to try things out that may not have a known

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:20.800
business connection yet, but, but, you know, um, you want to give them that,

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:23.560
that, that kind of opportunity, like, is that something you're able to do?

00:42:23.560 --> 00:42:25.959
And if so, uh, how do you do it?

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:26.760
Yeah.

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:27.879
A million dollar question.

00:42:27.959 --> 00:42:30.719
Um, so we do a few, a few strategies here.

00:42:30.719 --> 00:42:32.959
Um, this also is, you know, something that we continually

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:34.320
work on and try to promote.

00:42:34.840 --> 00:42:40.000
Um, we do, uh, planning each half with our partners.

00:42:40.479 --> 00:42:45.639
Um, and so we aim to get, and when we do this sort of biannual planning, we aim to

00:42:45.639 --> 00:42:50.239
get the most important projects to them on our roadmap so that we can jointly

00:42:50.239 --> 00:42:51.600
decide what those are.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:55.479
Um, and that allowed, you know, typically there within those larger projects,

00:42:55.479 --> 00:42:59.879
there's some room for, you know, new methods or innovation experimentation

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:04.040
while still working towards something that is key to the business and that, you

00:43:04.040 --> 00:43:06.080
know, partners have decided is important to them.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:10.439
Um, and so that works well for, uh, you know, trying to build in a bit more of

00:43:10.439 --> 00:43:15.080
that sort of, um, longer term project that, you know, allows the data scientists

00:43:15.080 --> 00:43:16.879
to dig in on the methodology side.

00:43:17.719 --> 00:43:20.959
But then, you know, of course we build flexibility into the process too.

00:43:20.959 --> 00:43:24.320
Things come up, you know, there may be, um, urgent things there are all the

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:28.399
time that come up that very important as well that, you know, folks work on.

00:43:28.879 --> 00:43:33.639
Um, and so we, you know, just sort of continually evaluate those and we're,

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:36.479
you know, I spend a ton of time just having conversations about resourcing

00:43:36.479 --> 00:43:39.760
and making trade-offs on what the team is working on, um, you know, I see

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:41.280
that as a key role of a manager.

00:43:42.439 --> 00:43:45.959
We also do, we have a good tradition of quarterly career chats.

00:43:46.040 --> 00:43:49.879
Um, so I do quarterly chats with everyone on my team, talk about their,

00:43:49.959 --> 00:43:53.360
you know, chance to zoom out and talk longer term about their interests.

00:43:53.360 --> 00:43:56.479
And from there I find out, um, you know, what kind of projects are they

00:43:56.479 --> 00:43:59.399
interested in that they're not currently working on or other things they're working

00:43:59.399 --> 00:44:00.800
on that they're less interested in.

00:44:01.199 --> 00:44:04.719
Um, there's of course, you know, you have to find the business need, right?

00:44:04.719 --> 00:44:05.760
We're not a research team.

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:11.159
We don't do sort of, um, you know, pure R&D work, um, but often by just

00:44:11.159 --> 00:44:14.719
having a good grasp on where people want to go and what they're interested in.

00:44:14.719 --> 00:44:17.199
You know, when I hear about new projects, I'm able to help target

00:44:17.199 --> 00:44:19.040
those appropriately to folks.

00:44:20.800 --> 00:44:21.120
Awesome.

00:44:21.719 --> 00:44:21.959
Thanks.

00:44:21.959 --> 00:44:25.840
A lot of that sounds familiar and stuff that I'm trying to do better as well.

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:29.719
Yeah, it's a continual process for sure.

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:30.439
Yeah.

00:44:32.159 --> 00:44:35.280
I was just making a note of the quarterly career chats too.

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:40.080
And I was just curious how, like, how do you frame that with your direct reports?

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:43.280
Like, is that an actual formal process that they go through

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:44.800
or just informal conversation?

00:44:45.479 --> 00:44:48.399
So the first time when I have a new direct report, either new to

00:44:48.399 --> 00:44:52.800
Stripe or new to reporting to me, I ask them, you know, it's fairly,

00:44:52.840 --> 00:44:54.280
you know, a more structured chat.

00:44:54.280 --> 00:44:58.040
We go through their career history and ask a lot of questions about the decisions

00:44:58.040 --> 00:45:00.520
that they've made along their way and their interests and, you know, what

00:45:00.520 --> 00:45:04.280
brought them to Stripe and, you know, a lot of, um, sort of just getting to

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:05.879
understand their career motivations.

00:45:06.439 --> 00:45:10.159
Um, for subsequent ones, um, it is more open.

00:45:10.520 --> 00:45:14.199
Um, a lot of folks, you know, have a more structured idea of what

00:45:14.199 --> 00:45:15.159
they want from their career.

00:45:15.159 --> 00:45:17.159
And we might talk through that plan each time.

00:45:17.639 --> 00:45:21.120
Um, I'll often come with, you know, questions or new frameworks that I'm

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:24.320
thinking about from how to think about your career and bring those.

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:28.439
Um, you know, some folks are either earlier or more open or

00:45:28.479 --> 00:45:30.080
less sure about their career.

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:33.159
And in that case, you know, I might direct the conversation a little bit more.

00:45:33.199 --> 00:45:35.239
So it's fairly tailored to the individual.

00:45:37.959 --> 00:45:38.479
Thank you.

00:45:39.239 --> 00:45:39.479
Okay.

00:45:39.479 --> 00:45:42.959
So I see two anonymous questions that are kind of on the same topic.

00:45:42.959 --> 00:45:45.080
So let me combine them both here.

00:45:45.479 --> 00:45:49.919
Um, but the questions are around, do you support both R and Python

00:45:49.919 --> 00:45:52.840
users on your team and what does that split look like?

00:45:53.399 --> 00:45:56.120
Um, actually let me ask that part first.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:45:58.239
So I don't, there are too many questions that one.

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:00.520
We do, we do.

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:06.360
We, um, we used to all of our forecasting are actually in recently, you know, Python

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:09.719
has stepped it up a bit and we've been doing a lot more in Python.

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:12.959
Um, part of the reason for that is that Stripe is somewhat more Python

00:46:12.959 --> 00:46:14.800
based in our infrastructure.

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:18.800
And so, um, doing it in Python allows us to integrate with the rest of

00:46:18.800 --> 00:46:20.919
Stripe systems, uh, much more easily.

00:46:21.479 --> 00:46:23.959
Um, we do, you know, support R here.

00:46:23.959 --> 00:46:25.280
We have our notebooks.

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:28.919
We have, uh, the ability to schedule jobs in R.

00:46:29.280 --> 00:46:33.360
Um, but I'd say it's, you know, more like 20 to 30% of data science usage

00:46:33.360 --> 00:46:34.800
and Python is a little bit more.

00:46:35.439 --> 00:46:37.239
Um, which, you know, R is close to my heart.

00:46:37.239 --> 00:46:40.040
That's the programming language that I started out in, in grad school.

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:44.080
And, um, you know, I could live in the tidy verse all day, but, um, you know,

00:46:44.080 --> 00:46:48.399
we use it a bit more for sort of analytical exploratory analysis work.

00:46:48.399 --> 00:46:51.879
I would say in Python, a bit more for, you know, in production jobs.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:57.760
In the, the followup question there was, do you encourage and support folks

00:46:57.760 --> 00:47:01.239
who want to learn one while being more proficient in the other?

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:02.679
Yeah, certainly.

00:47:02.679 --> 00:47:06.000
I just had someone on my team who, uh, was more proficient in R, but

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:07.360
wanted to learn more Python.

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:09.919
And we sort of designed a project for her that allowed her to do that.

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:11.879
Oh, awesome.

00:47:12.199 --> 00:47:18.919
Um, another anonymous question from earlier was, um, based on the fact that

00:47:18.919 --> 00:47:22.360
there would be underlying uncertainties in the forecast, how do you make your

00:47:22.360 --> 00:47:26.320
partner teams aware of and consider those uncertainties?

00:47:28.239 --> 00:47:29.479
Uh, yeah, yeah.

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:30.840
A complex question.

00:47:32.439 --> 00:47:34.040
Um, we talk about it a lot with them.

00:47:34.040 --> 00:47:35.479
We share the backtesting results.

00:47:35.479 --> 00:47:39.399
Those are usually helpful as sort of quantitative, you know, MAPE doesn't

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:44.040
tell you everything, but it tells you something about, um, you know, when we

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:47.000
looked over the past year, here's the amount of error that we saw.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.080
Here's how you might think about that going forward.

00:47:49.679 --> 00:47:55.080
Um, we, there's a lot of, you know, sort of fancier joint uncertainty throughout

00:47:55.080 --> 00:47:58.520
the hierarchy, uh, methodologies that we are exploring as well.

00:47:58.840 --> 00:48:03.399
I think uncertainty is one of the most useful concepts for, you know,

00:48:03.399 --> 00:48:04.760
forecasting within the business.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:09.959
Uh, but it's very hard to, uh, to, to sort of propagate the right level of

00:48:09.959 --> 00:48:11.479
uncertainty throughout the hierarchy.

00:48:11.879 --> 00:48:16.040
Um, you know, because you introduce uncertainty, both at the modeling, the

00:48:16.040 --> 00:48:19.719
initial modeling, you know, various points and in the reconciliation.

00:48:19.719 --> 00:48:24.199
And so, um, so that's, you know, somewhat, somewhat more of an interesting problem,

00:48:24.280 --> 00:48:29.159
um, to get to, uh, uncertain to get to uncertainty bands that you're actually

00:48:29.199 --> 00:48:30.040
confident in.

00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:33.320
Um, so we do that, you know, we explored from the statistical side, but we also

00:48:33.320 --> 00:48:36.360
from the business side, I just sort of take the perspective of, you know, you

00:48:36.360 --> 00:48:39.639
should, um, here's what we've seen historically, you know, you should expect

00:48:39.639 --> 00:48:42.919
some uncertainty in the forecast and then, you know, really digging in when

00:48:42.919 --> 00:48:44.679
we do see forecast misses.

00:48:48.040 --> 00:48:48.600
Thank you.

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:53.959
I saw on LinkedIn, I think it was a post maybe from a year ago where you were

00:48:53.959 --> 00:48:57.479
presenting on like managing a remote and globally.

00:48:57.479 --> 00:48:58.840
Distributed data science team.

00:48:59.399 --> 00:49:04.439
And it was curious if you have any tips that you'd like to share with us in terms

00:49:04.439 --> 00:49:06.520
of managing a team that's, that's all over.

00:49:07.320 --> 00:49:07.800
Yeah.

00:49:07.879 --> 00:49:08.120
Yeah.

00:49:08.120 --> 00:49:09.399
And this was true even pre COVID.

00:49:09.399 --> 00:49:15.000
So I have folks in Dublin, Ireland, uh, in New York, DC, I'm in Minnesota, folks

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.639
in SF and Seattle, I think that's it.

00:49:17.639 --> 00:49:21.080
So it's, you know, we're very distributed, have been for a while.

00:49:21.639 --> 00:49:25.000
Um, I talked a bit about the early stage technical feedback meetings that I

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:30.120
actually been a surprisingly useful thing to do for, um, just for making sure that

00:49:30.120 --> 00:49:32.439
we have that sort of weekly touch point with the team.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:36.199
Um, you know, you can do zoom happy hours and those kinds of things, and those

00:49:36.199 --> 00:49:39.719
are nice, but it's nice to have a little bit of structure and topic to know what

00:49:39.719 --> 00:49:41.159
we're trying to do and to be able to have.

00:49:41.800 --> 00:49:45.320
Um, you know, somewhat of a technical conversation in a, you know, again, very

00:49:45.320 --> 00:49:47.239
low stakes environment.

00:49:47.239 --> 00:49:50.199
We don't expect you to have a polished presentation, but, you know, much more of

00:49:50.199 --> 00:49:52.040
a rainstorm type atmosphere.

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:54.040
Um, so having that touch point has been really nice.

00:49:56.040 --> 00:49:57.000
Um, what else do we do?

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
Snacks, people love snacks.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:03.639
So I will, um, there are a number of services that, you know, you can send snacks, uh,

00:50:03.639 --> 00:50:07.560
to people that just, you know, I think there's a, there's a certain, you know, nice

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:10.840
feeling that people get by sharing the same snacks on zoom.

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:11.399
It's a good one.

00:50:11.959 --> 00:50:15.159
Trying to remember what other, what are our other strategies?

00:50:15.159 --> 00:50:17.000
I think just, oh, focusing on onboarding.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:17.879
That's another big one.

00:50:17.879 --> 00:50:21.320
Um, with, you know, when folks start remotely, that's a very different experience.

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:25.959
Then it used to be where they were in the office, you know, among everybody in a

00:50:25.959 --> 00:50:27.719
starting class, seeing everyone.

00:50:28.280 --> 00:50:31.239
Um, so I focus really closely on new folks.

00:50:31.239 --> 00:50:33.479
I meet with them every day when they're starting.

00:50:33.479 --> 00:50:37.879
I, I, you know, I'm not, I'm not, I'm not, I'm not, I'm not, I'm not, I'm not, I'm not

00:50:37.879 --> 00:50:38.439
new folks.

00:50:38.439 --> 00:50:40.600
I meet with them every day when they're starting.

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:44.520
I, uh, set up meetings with the relevant people that they need to meet.

00:50:44.520 --> 00:50:46.199
I make sure they have the resources that they need.

00:50:46.199 --> 00:50:51.239
I focus, you know, the first month or so just focus really closely on new folks and

00:50:51.239 --> 00:50:52.280
making sure they get integrated.

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:53.800
Cause it doesn't happen naturally.

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:55.800
Um, in a remote world, you really have to work at that.

00:50:57.479 --> 00:50:58.280
Absolutely.

00:50:58.280 --> 00:51:02.199
I love the point of like, even just sharing the same snacks, like something little

00:51:02.199 --> 00:51:06.919
like that and Libby, I see you timed your comment perfectly to when Dara was actually

00:51:06.919 --> 00:51:09.000
talking about onboarding too.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:12.439
So just want to see if you had any follow-up question on that Libby.

00:51:14.040 --> 00:51:15.800
No, that was really, really well-timed.

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:18.439
I asked it and then Dara answered it.

00:51:18.439 --> 00:51:25.320
Um, yeah, I think onboarding is a really tough thing in data science in general and then

00:51:25.320 --> 00:51:27.080
extra tough when everybody's remote.

00:51:27.080 --> 00:51:27.719
Right.

00:51:27.719 --> 00:51:32.760
And so I was kind of wondering what, you know, emphasis you put on that and how it

00:51:32.760 --> 00:51:36.280
worked and if you buddy people up and, um, things like that.

00:51:36.280 --> 00:51:39.560
But you really hit the nail on the head that it has to be intentional.

00:51:39.560 --> 00:51:42.679
Does not going to happen spontaneously, right?

00:51:42.679 --> 00:51:47.000
People aren't going to just integrate into a group and seamlessly work with everybody.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:48.439
There has to be some intention there.

00:51:48.439 --> 00:51:49.479
So that was good to hear.

00:51:50.120 --> 00:51:55.080
If you have any expansion on that, I'd love to hear, but if not, you did a great job answering.

00:51:56.040 --> 00:51:57.239
Yeah, you hit most of the points.

00:51:57.239 --> 00:51:58.600
We do have spin-up buddies.

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:03.639
And so people get paired up with an existing data scientist or data analyst that, um, you

00:52:03.639 --> 00:52:06.919
know, they can meet with and ask any question to at any point.

00:52:06.919 --> 00:52:10.919
There's a Stripe wide sort of onboarding curriculum that, you know, teaches people about

00:52:10.919 --> 00:52:13.320
payments and, um, the Stripe product.

00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:16.520
And then we have a data science specific curriculum as well.

00:52:16.520 --> 00:52:18.360
You know, how to set up your environment.

00:52:18.360 --> 00:52:19.800
How do we use Git at Stripe?

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:22.360
You know, some of the more technical classes that we run.

00:52:23.879 --> 00:52:25.399
And those are both pretty helpful.

00:52:25.959 --> 00:52:29.639
But yeah, from there, it is very much just like making sure to meet with the right.

00:52:29.639 --> 00:52:30.679
Oh, and we have a spin-up project.

00:52:30.679 --> 00:52:33.080
So that's the other thing that we do, you know, very intentionally.

00:52:33.080 --> 00:52:39.159
We plan a sort of, uh, well-scoped project that we give to new folks that should allow

00:52:39.159 --> 00:52:40.760
them some room for exploration.

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:45.479
It should be important to the business, but not, um, business critical need it next week

00:52:45.479 --> 00:52:49.479
type of project so that they can, you know, ship something that is important, but not

00:52:49.479 --> 00:52:51.399
feel that sort of time pressure immediately.

00:52:51.399 --> 00:52:54.360
They need to have some time to, you know, spin up on our systems and meet folks.

00:52:57.159 --> 00:52:57.879
That's great.

00:52:57.879 --> 00:53:00.199
Who comes up with that project?

00:53:00.199 --> 00:53:01.399
The manager does.

00:53:01.399 --> 00:53:01.899
Okay.

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:08.840
And just do like the newly onboarded people kind of like work together on that and share

00:53:09.639 --> 00:53:10.139
results.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:11.399
They do.

00:53:11.399 --> 00:53:13.159
Cause there's enough engineers on the data science side.

00:53:13.159 --> 00:53:15.080
It's typically just sort of one person per project.

00:53:16.760 --> 00:53:17.260
Cool.

00:53:18.199 --> 00:53:23.159
So I know we're getting to the end of our time here, but one question I, I love to ask

00:53:23.159 --> 00:53:28.199
people when we have time is what is the best career advice that you've ever received?

00:53:28.760 --> 00:53:31.479
Or maybe not best, but something that sticks in your mind.

00:53:32.520 --> 00:53:36.919
Something that sticks in my mind is to think about choosing the wild card when you're

00:53:36.919 --> 00:53:38.439
presented with multiple choices.

00:53:39.479 --> 00:53:44.360
So, you know, for me, when I was choosing my PhD advisor, I had two rotation, you do

00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:45.159
three rotations, right?

00:53:45.159 --> 00:53:50.439
I had two rotations that I had planned ahead of time that I knew I was very interested

00:53:50.439 --> 00:53:51.959
in the research that would go really well.

00:53:53.080 --> 00:53:56.120
You know, I thought, and they, they did both go really well and I really liked those labs.

00:53:56.120 --> 00:54:00.360
And then the third one was you know, this brand new professor, I would be the first

00:54:00.360 --> 00:54:01.159
grad student.

00:54:01.159 --> 00:54:04.280
It was a little bit outside the kind of research that I had done before.

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:07.639
So I thought, you know, I'll just do this wild card rotation.

00:54:08.280 --> 00:54:11.560
And of course, you know, that was the lab that I ended up joining.

00:54:11.560 --> 00:54:16.199
I was the first grad student and ended up having just this fantastic experience with

00:54:16.919 --> 00:54:18.199
my advisor and with the research.

00:54:18.840 --> 00:54:22.679
And that also, you know, has held true as I've made other career decisions along the

00:54:22.679 --> 00:54:27.000
way, you know, choosing to go to Stripe rather than stay in something in biology, choosing

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.479
to go to data science rather than do an academic postdoc.

00:54:30.360 --> 00:54:36.040
You know, sometimes that wild card choice is, can feel a little scary, but also kind

00:54:36.040 --> 00:54:36.679
of enticing.

00:54:36.679 --> 00:54:42.679
And, you know, for me, just trying to not be afraid to choose that option among choices

00:54:42.679 --> 00:54:43.479
has worked out well.

00:54:45.959 --> 00:54:46.439
Thank you.

00:54:46.439 --> 00:54:47.320
That's great advice.

00:54:48.120 --> 00:54:53.800
